                      <p class="product-text">Unlike measurements of pressure or temperature fields, measuring precipitation is challenging due to its highly dynamic, heterogeneous spatial distribution
                        and stochastic nature. To that extent, a broad range of rain rates can be observed within a 1 to 3 hours long event at a single location. In addition,
                        precipitation is strongly influenced by large-scale patterns of natural variability. The most recent Fifth Assessment report released in 2014 by the
                        Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) indicates that climate change’s impact on global precipitation changes is still not evident, but already
                        had an adverse impact on heavy precipitation events. As a result, a better understanding of rainfall dynamics in response to climate change is essential.
                      </p>
                      <p class="product-text">To estimate rainfall intensity (generally expressed in mm per unity of time), two types of sources are available: rain gauges or remote-based instruments
                        (satellite, radar). But in many developing countries, the rain gauge network is too sparse to capture temporal and spatial variability of rainfall
                        distribution, and is insufficient to estimate future monetary losses. In addition, most gauges are in towns and cities, not agricultural areas which render
                        them ineffective for larger scale index insurance projects. Different solutions exist to recreate time-series at local positions. Of which, advanced
                        geostatistical methods have been developed to simulate synthetic rainfall data instead of using gridding methods such as interpolation and kriging from stations.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        Known as weather generators, these geostatistical models allow to generate synthetic time series of atmospheric variables at local sites. Many weather
                        generators were developed along the past fifty years, and comparing each one to another is a difficult if not impossible task. When the variable to
                        simulate is rain, <em>stochastic modeling of space-time rainfall field</em> generators can account for spatial rainfall distribution and temporal climate
                        variability. In other words, they allow to simulate both multiple spatial rainfall distributions for a given rainfall (spatial variability) and multiple
                        distributions of rainfall intensities in time (temporal variability). Stochastic generators are useful throughout many applications to better understand
                        rainfall probabilistic structure, as input to feed hydrologic and process-based crop models, as a statistical downscaling method in Global Climate Models
                        or Regional Climate Models and to estimate radars measurement uncertainty.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        In this context, Hadley Innovation is developing a stochastic generator to simulate realistic rainfall fields with spatial and temporal variability. From
                        ground observations data, statistical analysis of rainfall distribution is first achieved to infer parameters in the rainfall simulator. In output,
                        relevant information is generated at sites with no previous measurements, or where only short data series are available. These data are intended to improve
                        weather index insurance design and to act as an innovative insurance product addressing developing countries challenges.
                      </p>
